The issue is that the notification is being created but not showing up visibly. This is a common problem with Android emulators. Let's troubleshoot step by step:

1. Check Notification Channel Importance
The most common issue is that the channel importance is set too low. Let's modify your home_screen.dart:

dart
void showNotification() async{
    AndroidNotificationDetails androidDetails = 
        AndroidNotificationDetails(
            "demo-notification-aniket",
            "Notifications Aniket",
            channelDescription: 'It\'s Demo Description To Test Notification',
            priority: Priority.high, // Changed from max to high
            importance: Importance.high, // Changed from max to high
            playSound: true, // Add sound
            enableVibration: true, // Add vibration
            visibility: NotificationVisibility.public, // Make it visible everywhere
        );

    DarwinNotificationDetails iosDetails =
        DarwinNotificationDetails(
          presentAlert: true,
          presentBadge: true,
          presentSound: true,
        );

    NotificationDetails notiDetails = NotificationDetails(
      android: androidDetails,
      iOS: iosDetails
    );
 
    try {
      await notificationPlugin.show(
        0, //Notification ID
        "Sample Notification Title",
        "This is Notification Body",
        notiDetails,
      );
      print("Notification shown successfully");
    } catch (e){
      print('Error showing notification: $e');
    }
  }
2. Check Android Notification Settings
In your emulator:

Go to Settings > Apps & notifications > Notifications

Check if your app has notification permission enabled

Make sure "Do Not Disturb" mode is turned off

3. Verify Notification Channel Creation
Add this function to check if your channel is properly created:

dart
void checkNotificationSettings() async {
  try {
    // Check if notifications are enabled
    bool? result = await notificationPlugin
        .resolvePlatformSpecificImplementation<AndroidFlutterLocalNotificationsPlugin>()
        ?.areNotificationsEnabled();
    
    print("Notifications enabled: $result");
    
    // List all notification channels
    var channels = await notificationPlugin
        .resolvePlatformSpecificImplementation<AndroidFlutterLocalNotificationsPlugin>()
        ?.getNotificationChannels();
    
    print("Available channels: $channels");
  } catch (e) {
    print("Error checking notification settings: $e");
  }
}
Call this function in your initState:

dart
@override
void initState() {
  super.initState();
  WidgetsBinding.instance.addPostFrameCallback((_) {
    checkNotificationSettings();
  });
}
4. Alternative: Create Notification Channel Separately
Sometimes creating the channel explicitly helps:

dart
void createNotificationChannel() async {
  final android = AndroidFlutterLocalNotificationsPlugin();
  
  await android.createNotificationChannel(AndroidNotificationChannel(
    'demo-notification-aniket',
    'Notifications Aniket',
    description: 'It\'s Demo Description To Test Notification',
    importance: Importance.high,
    playSound: true,
  ));
}
Call this in your initState before showing notifications.

5. Test with Simple Notification First
Try this minimal version:

dart
void showSimpleNotification() async {
  try {
    await notificationPlugin.show(
      0,
      'Test Title',
      'Test Body',
      NotificationDetails(
        android: AndroidNotificationDetails(
          'basic_channel',
          'Basic Channel',
          channelDescription: 'Basic notifications',
          importance: Importance.high,
          priority: Priority.high,
        ),
      ),
    );
    print("Simple notification shown");
  } catch (e) {
    print('Error: $e');
  }
}
6. Check Emulator Settings
Swipe down from the top of the emulator screen to see the notification panel

Make sure the emulator is not in "Do Not Disturb" mode

Check if notifications are muted in the emulator settings

7. Debug Steps
Add this debug code to see what's happening:

dart
void debugNotification() async {
  print("Starting notification...");
  
  var android = AndroidNotificationDetails(
    'debug_channel',
    'Debug Channel',
    channelDescription: 'For debugging',
    importance: Importance.high,
    priority: Priority.high,
    playSound: true,
  );
  
  var details = NotificationDetails(android: android);
  
  print("Showing notification with details: $details");
  
  try {
    await notificationPlugin.show(
      999, 
      'DEBUG TITLE',
      'DEBUG BODY - You should see this!',
      details,
    );
    print("✅ Notification show() completed without error");
  } catch (e) {
    print("❌ Error: $e");
  }
}
8. Restart the Emulator
Sometimes the emulator notification system gets stuck:

Close the emulator

Start a fresh emulator instance

Run your app again

Try these steps in order and let me know what the debug output shows. The most likely issue is the notification channel importance or emulator notification settings.
